If the dictionary defines confidence as a feeling of certainty, then where does that certainty come from?

For so many, I see it deeply tied to the results that they get in their life. If they win, they feel great, but if they lose their confidence crumbles. 

If that certainty in ourselves is conditional on us always having to succeed, then what happens when we don’t? It puts our confidence in a very fragile position. One that we aren’t actually in control of.

What if instead, our certainty in ourselves didn’t come from getting a certain result (because we can never truly guarantee the result, just the effort that we put in), but instead from knowing that we’ll be ok at the end of the day regardless of the outcome.

No matter the outcome of a situation, whether we fail, fall short, get hurt or let down, it doesn't have to rock our fundamental sense of who we are, what we know about ourselves, and our ability to carry on moving forwards in the future despite a setback. That’s true core confidence.

One of the keys to get to this place in our core confidence is deriving our validation internally (knowing our values and who we want to be) as opposed to externally (the results of our life and what other people think of us).

Learning how to make this transformation is a complete game changer. It permeates into every area of our life and has always been one of the core teachings from my Retreat process.

If you’re ready to starting living your life through a different lens that will dramatically alter your confidence in life, I'd love for you to join us on our final Virtual Retreat of the year, September 24-26.
  
All you need to do is head to MHVirtualRetreat.com (or tap the link in my IG Profile) and book your free consultation with one of my trusted Retreat Specialists: Michael, Emma, or Lottie. 

This amazing team has been working with me on this process for years and are on hand to hear your story. Booking this time to speak privately with one of them will help you clarify your goals and start you on the path to making serious and lasting change.

node.title: It’s time we changed the way we see confidence.

And when I recently watched the new documentary Roadrunner: A Film About Anthony Bourdain, it drove home some of the reasons why his death left so many people reeling.

It’s not always easy to talk about the messier aspects of life, but it is important. And the more we can help each other during the more challenging moments, the more we’ll be able to access the truth and beauty Bourdain aspired to.
 
Here for you,
 
Matthew x
 
P.S. This week’s video means a lot to me, and I hope you’ll share it with any friend who’s going through a tough time.

node.text:
but this is more likely to be the ego loving our external achievements than a genuine expression of unconditional self-love. 

The danger with this kind of self-love is that the moment we experience a setback in life (which inevitably we will at some point), we simply crash back into old negative patterns internally because we find it harder to practice self-love when we’re having a tough time or not accomplishing something.
 
True self-love is something we should try to cultivate in the more difficult moments in our lives. 
 
To do this, we have to start seeing ourselves through a different lens.  
 
Imagine somebody you love coming to you during a difficult times in their life and saying:

“I’ve messed up and I need your advice.”
“I made this huge mistake and I don’t know what to do.”
“I’m really struggling with insecurity and my confidence is so low right now.”

We intuitively know how we’d treat that person that we love and care about. We’d treat them with love, kindness, and support. We see their potential. We become a team mate in helping them figure it out. We are an ally who lifts them up, not a ruthless judge who sentences them to more days, months or years of feeling bad about themselves.

That’s the kind of relationship we need to start cultivating with ourselves. 

Do you want to start cultivating a more loving relationship with yourself? Are you ready to become a better team mate to YOU? 

Join thousands of people across the world who have signed up for free to my 30-Day Confidence Challenge on July 21. We will measurably improve your confidence together over a single month, and start changing your relationship with yourself in the process. Consider this 30 days to make your entire year happier and more peaceful. It only takes 10 seconds and it's free to sign up at mhchallenge.com or by tapping the link in my IG profile.

in ones own abilities. But abilities come from taking action. If we take action consistently enough, for long enough, we create new reference points for what is possible. These reference points become the basis for a new level of confidence in ourselves. 

And yet, so often I hear people talking about 'believing' first. If you can get to a place of believing you can with zero reference points, you have a better imagination than I do. 

I personally don't sit around trying to believe I can. But how then can we take action if we don't have any initial belief? By remembering that belief isn't necessary to take action. Necessity is. The necessity for things to be better than they are now. Genuine pain and deep dissatisfaction is enough to create action. 

Confidence then becomes the reward we receive for this action, not the prerequisite for the action we take. 

Confidence isn’t something we simply have or don’t have, it’s something that is built and earned. It grows over time in proportion to the action we take—actions that over time create new reference points for what we’re capable of.

Are you ready to build more confidence in your life in a real and measurable way? It doesn't matter if you're afraid of the next steps, or confused about the way forward. All you need to get started is a decision to get away from where you are right now. In other words, if you feel dissatisfied or in pain, that's great, we can work with that. 

Bring your dissatisfaction and your pain to my final Virtual Retreat of the year this September 24 – 26 and we will use it as the fuel to create a blueprint that will change your life, your confidence and your happiness. 

This immersive 3-day coaching event has been custom designed by me and will be streamed live to you in the comfort of your own home. Simply tap the link in my IG profile or head to MHVirtualRetreat.com to book a free consultation with one of my Retreat Specialists, who can answer any questions you have and tell you more about this transformative process.

node.text:
You’re excited for a date tonight, but then you see it . . . your own reflection in a mirror. Your eyes pinpoint that one insecurity and your nerves kick in with one repetitive thought: I CAN’T DO THIS.
 
In this week’s video, my brother Stephen and I dig into a fascinating study in which nearly half of the people surveyed said they would call off a date if they weren’t feeling great about their body that day.
 
We’re not talking about serious body/mental issues here. Think more along the lines of a bad hair day, a prominent zit, or the extra pounds you gained from that holiday weekend. Insecurities like these cause many people to preemptively reject themselves because of something the other person likely wouldn’t have noticed or cared about.

If the dictionary defines confidence as a feeling of certainty, then where does that certainty come from?

For so many, I see it deeply tied to the results that they get in their life. If they win, they feel great, but if they lose their confidence crumbles. 

If that certainty in ourselves is conditional on us always having to succeed, then what happens when we don’t? It puts our confidence in a very fragile position. One that we aren’t actually in control of.

What if instead, our certainty in ourselves didn’t come from getting a certain result (because we can never truly guarantee the result, just the effort that we put in), but instead from knowing that we’ll be ok at the end of the day regardless of the outcome.

No matter the outcome of a situation, whether we fail, fall short, get hurt or let down, it doesn't have to rock our fundamental sense of who we are, what we know about ourselves, and our ability to carry on moving forwards in the future despite a setback. That’s true core confidence.

One of the keys to get to this place in our core confidence is deriving our validation internally (knowing our values and who we want to be) as opposed to externally (the results of our life and what other people think of us).

Learning how to make this transformation is a complete game changer. It permeates into every area of our life and has always been one of the core teachings from my Retreat process.

If you’re ready to starting living your life through a different lens that will dramatically alter your confidence in life, I'd love for you to join us on our final Virtual Retreat of the year, September 24-26.

This amazing team has been working with me on this process for years and are on hand to hear your story. Booking this time to speak privately with one of them will help you clarify your goals and start you on the path to making serious and lasting change.

node.text:
Assassins ignore everything in their path but their target. In love, this can look like waiting for someone really attractive to show up before you start to smile and be sociable. It's being cold and distant with everyone except the one person you have your eye on.
 
The irony of this is that when you finally engage with the person, you're so nervous and out of practice that you freeze up anyway.
 
We have to remove this very goal-driven mindset and instead start focusing on bringing warmth with us wherever we go—to everyone we can.
 
Focus on creating moments, even if you're not interested in someone romantically. Live life, meet people, and expand your circle of friends until one day, you meet someone who really piques your interest.
 
And when you do, recognize that the starting point is just to have a moment with them: share an observation, give a compliment, ask them what they're drinking, notice their dog. Your job is not to seduce them, but simply to open the doors of possibility. If you keep doing that, sooner or later, someone special will walk in.

And when I recently watched the new documentary Roadrunner: A Film About Anthony Bourdain, it drove home some of the reasons why his death left so many people reeling.

It’s not always easy to talk about the messier aspects of life, but it is important. And the more we can help each other during the more challenging moments, the more we’ll be able to access the truth and beauty Bourdain aspired to.
 
Here for you,
 
Matthew x
 
P.S. This week’s video means a lot to me, and I hope you’ll share it with any friend who’s going through a tough time.

node.text:
Whether or not you’re familiar with Bourdain’s work, you won’t want to miss this week’s video, in which my brother @stephenhhussey and I unpack some of the life-changing lessons from the film, including how to:
 
• Live a richer life by getting out of your “bubble.”
 
• Stop comparing your achievements with those of others.

 • Overcome FOMO and the need for everything to go perfectly.

Tap the link in my IG Profile or head to howtogettheguy.com/blog to watch this week's new video and tell me what you think in the comments.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Matthew Hussey on July 30, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing and text that says 'Matthew Hussey @matthewhussey If you ever feel you're "bothering" someone, remember this.. people WANT to fall in love.'.

node.text: We so often worry that by approaching someone, asking them out, or paying them a compliment, we'll be "bothering" them. The ones in relationships? Perhaps (though no one hates a compliment). The ones who are too stressed out to pay attention? Maybe. But the majority of people who haven't found love want to find it. I'm not talking about coming on too strong. This is just about taking the step to interact with someone. You're not bothering them; you're giving them a shot at their dream. They may take it or reject it. But do not apologize for it. Taking that risk might be the greatest thing you ever do for someone else.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Matthew Hussey on July 29, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of 1 person and text that says 'Matthew Hussey Craft a big enough life that it quickly makes the person who ghosted you irrelevant.'.

node.text:
A conversation taken from me and my brother @stephenhhussey in our membership program: 

MATTHEW: If someone ghosts you, that’s a good thing to learn about them now. 
 
STEPHEN: I’m not trying to stop ghosting in my life. I’m trying to put myself out there in the best way possible so I don’t have to care about the one or two people who ghost. 
 
MATTHEW: Exactly. The fact that they ghosted you means they don’t deserve any more of your mental time and energy. Don't waste energy obsessing over it. Instead, out-live it. Craft a life full enough that it quickly makes the ghoster irrelevant.
